Text:
Dangerous for Texas. 
"The Lone Star State could bear the brunt of this latest broadside." https://t.co/JnxAlHmgfg

Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: No wonder people think our campaign finance system is rigged when you can make $20,000 in illegal contributions, be charged, plead guilty, be sentenced, and then receive a pardon. We need to get big money out of politics, end PACs, reverse Citizens United, get our Democracy back.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "We'd go further to argue that one way to strengthen American security is to bolster our economy. And getting into a trade war with key NAFTA and European partners will undercut our economic prospects." https://t.co/FvLQPRDuNB
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
There could be no state hit harder than Texas. More than 2.6 million jobs at risk overall with the new steel and aluminum tariffs threatening 470,000. 
https://t.co/pyRCntKoJF
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
As I said at our Midland town hall back in April, whether it's the energy we produce, the cotton we grow, the cattle we raise, all of this has a connection to the rest of the world. These trade wars are really bad for the Texas economy.
https://t.co/70izgiC53r
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Texas could be hit harder than any other state by these kinds of tariffs. Trump’s trade policies will devastate our state, businesses, & economy. Senator Cruz should have explained that to the president while they were riding together last month.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: You could start with the fact that Texas is home to the San Antonio-based Toyota manufacturing plant and the company’s new North America HQ in Plano. No automaker will be hit harder by these tariffs. Prices of cars will have to go up.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Could point out that Texas imports more steel and aluminum than any other state in the U.S. That we rely upon those metals for a booming energy sector. That these new tariffs will cause layoffs.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Could talk about agriculture. How Texas is a top producer of cotton, wheat, corn, beef, sorghum -- all of which are targeted by tariffs. One Texan said, “you couldn’t have picked a list of commodities that were more representative of our growers.”
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Those in the Lubbock region know this better than anyone: our share of US-produced cotton actually makes up nearly half of exports to China, valuing $450M annually. It’s our state’s number two commodity behind beef cattle.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Could explain what sorghum is. That Texas produces more of it than any other state besides Kansas. That China accounts for more than 70% of US sorghum exports and our share of exported sorghum is 25% of the country’s, accounting for $209 million annually.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Or talk about how the Pecan Capital of the World is right here in Texas. And that our state is the second largest producer of pecans nationwide. Tariffs hitting pecan growers in San Saba and grapefruit growers in the Rio Grande Valley don’t help our state either.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In particular, these tariffs and trade wars threaten our small and medium-sized businesses, which make up more than 90% of all Texas exporters. Their customers abroad support more than 3 million jobs across Texas.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It comes down to the fact that TX is among the nation’s most active states for trade. We rank first in exports. $97 billion in exports to Mexico alone. Our communities depend on it -- from agricultural centers to Houston where exports account for nearly one-fifth of the economy.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We need a senator who is not afraid to raise these issues with the president. Someone who will stand up to him when he is going to hurt Texas jobs and economic growth. Who will be a voice for the 28 million of us who call Texas home. That’s what I want to do.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I #WearOrange for the young people across Texas who are forcing the conversation and joining their peers nationwide in leading the effort to #EndGunViolence. https://t.co/77ay66sMSJ
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We absolutely should not be deporting veterans from the country they put their lives on the line to serve. Authored legislation to make this right. Let's have a vote on it. https://t.co/U3PZCkEy8D
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
Texans mind. 1 in 4 Texas jobs depend on trade with Mexico. Nearly 1 million jobs in our state are linked to trade with our southern neighbor. Last year alone, Texas had $97 billion in exports to Mexico. 
https://t.co/dKxysYTIas
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Beyond grateful that our fellow Texas native Leon Bridges would showcase the beauty and character of El Paso in his new music video. https://t.co/kxulnBCmAl
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
For years, there was a lack of accountability when it came to civilian casualties caused by US military operations. So I introduced a provision to require an annual report. Passed with a bipartisan vote & the president signed it. 2017 report is now out.
https://t.co/QKM6E0m986
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: If we are to be engaged in nations across the world tonight, we should have a full understanding of how our decisions are taking the lives of civilians. While questions remain, this report is a first step and will help increase accountability for the impact we're having abroad.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I don't think you can be too gay to buy a cake. I don't think you can be too gay to open your caring family to one of TX's 30,000 kids in the foster care system. Let's end this discrimination. Let's pass the Equality Act. Let's ensure equal justice under law for LGBTQ Americans.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Spotted a yard sign riding down Trawood on the east side this morning! https://t.co/OgHHSq6fq1
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: This one takes 18 characters not 18 seconds: nope, POTUS can't. https://t.co/fHNXm3MsDO
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Representatives should be accountable to those they're sworn to serve. I hold an El Paso town hall every month. A veterans town hall every quarter. Each one public & in person where any person can ask any question, share any ideas, give any criticism. Today, we held our 9⃣6⃣th.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Corpus Christi Caller-Times Editorial Board: "He and his hard-working parents are another country's loss and our gain. It's how this nation was built and what made it great." https://t.co/Sq8qJMiy21
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Excellent reporting from the Dallas Morning News. Reminds us that the press is more important than ever. We need these stories uncovered and told. A 3 part piece with each showing exactly what happens when we allow corporate profits to come before people. https://t.co/f7Wk5nrmYo
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Part 1: TX pays companies billions to arrange care for foster children, disabled children, chronically sick children. Every $ they don’t spend on care can be used to pay millions in executive bonuses. TX knows companies are skimping on care to make profits but failed to stop it.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In Mesquite, D’ashon was born 3 months early, unable to breathe on his own. But with proper care, he was doing better. Then a health care company decided he didn’t need round-the-clock nursing care. The decision would save them as much as $500/day. It cost D’ashon everything.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: But the company received no sanctions or fines. In fact, Texas handed them tens of thousands more medically fragile kids to care for in 2017. They received a brand new contract worth more than $440 million a year.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Part 2: Texas used to pay for long-term nursing home care directly, writing checks to doctors & home-care agencies. But now our state turns over many of its health programs to private companies, allowing corporations to profit as they skimp on essential care for disabled adults.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In San Antonio, Heather was nearly completely paralyzed. She found joy in being visited by nurses. But then the company TX paid to manage her care cut the hours of her nurses. She was alone for 17 hours a day, unable to move, and in pain. All to save the company a few bucks.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Part 3: The companies TX hires & pays billions to care for its sickest citizens have been overstating the number of doctors & specialists available to treat them. DMN called every doctor asking if they could schedule a new-patient appointment for a foster child. Only 9% could.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In Kosse, Marta looked for a psychiatrist for her 12-year-old foster son whose previous provider had retired. Off his medication for weeks, the boy threatened a sibling with a knife and had a mental breakdown at school. Needed to see a doctor but the wait was 6 months.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In these stories & the many more that still need to be uncovered, the heroes are the patients, the parents, the families, & the caregivers who never give up. Who give a voice to the voiceless & fight with everything they've got to be treated with the dignity we all deserve.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: A reminder that instead of allowing profits and corporations to control decision making and care, we need to achieve guaranteed universal healthcare for every single one of us. So that no person is priced out. And so we are all well enough to contribute to our full potential.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
A story of renewal that we've seen across TX as we've driven to nearly every county. Places like Goldthwaite where we held a town hall in a restaurant newly opened by immigrants from Jalisco. Their entrepreneurship was injecting new life into the community
https://t.co/Zr6tU9Wt0N
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: “Each time a man stands up for an ideal, or acts to improve the lot of others, or strikes out against injustice, he sends forth a tiny ripple of hope, and crossing each other...those ripples build a current that can sweep down the mightiest walls of oppression & resistance.” -RFK https://t.co/nJMNZb4h6h

Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
We've got to allow doctors to prescribe what's in the best interests of our veterans, including cannabis. The research is clear: we need to stop denying legal access to something that will significantly ease the pain many of our veterans are living with.
https://t.co/LkkwUzznra
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "While VA physicians are quick to prescribe powerful drug cocktails (opiates & benzodiazepines) in response to service-related conditions, the federal government continues to deny veterans legal access to a demonstrably safer alternative treatment option — medical cannabis."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "Never mind that medical cannabis is now legal in 30 states, or that its medicinal value is recognized by health experts such as the American College of Physicians, the American Public Health Assoc, & the American Nurses Assoc as a safer alternative to many legal treatments."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "Veterans suffer chronic severe pain at rates disproportionately higher than their civilian counterparts (roughly 40% higher according to the National Institutes of Health), helping to explain why the opioid crisis has hit veterans at a rate two times the national average."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: This is the scene right now in Longview, Texas where they're opening up one of our volunteer led field offices. Grateful for all of your grassroots work in Longview! Looking forward to our next town hall with you. https://t.co/HYd43giRUF
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
James Byrd Jr. was brutally murdered in a hate crime 20 years ago today. Chained to the back of a truck and dragged for miles through Jasper, Texas, he was killed because of the color of his skin. This is what happened in the years that followed [1/7]
https://t.co/guuswHsYy8
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: To remember Byrd and address what had occurred, there were efforts to pass the Matthew Shepard and James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Prevention Act. For years, it faced sharp opposition in Congress including from Texas reps, senators, and our current Attorney General Jeff Sessions.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It failed in 2001, 2004, 2005. In 2007, it passed the House but failed in the Senate. When it finally passed the Senate, it received a veto threat from the president and eventually failed again. But advocates across the country refused to give up. Continued marching for progress.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: So in 2009 with a new president, they tried again. Though opposed by some Texas reps, it passed the House. It went to the Senate. Newly appointed AG Eric Holder testified in favor. With 5 members crossing the aisle, it passed. On Oct 28, President Barack Obama signed it into law.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: My colleague John Lewis reminds us of something Dr King used to say: there is nothing more powerful than the rhythm of marching feet. For James & Matthew, advocates marched on, accepting they might fail at first but knowing their incremental progress would eventually cause change
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: For it's never enlightened members of Congress or presidents who've gotten the hard things done. It's the people who've applied the pressure that has formed the political will to force them to get the right thing done. We see that in every civil rights fight of our history.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In the memory of James Byrd Jr., in the memory of Matthew Shepard, in the memory of those killed in hate crimes before and after their time, we must continue the march for civil rights, equal rights, and a more just America where we are all treated with dignity and respect.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Taking kids from parents who’ve crossed half a continent to bring them to safety. Traumatizing their children for life, staining our conscience. The wealthiest, most powerful country on the planet turning our backs, building walls. Losing ourselves. https://t.co/JZFFZ9emng
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Important read. The Affordable Care Act's provision protecting those with pre-existing conditions is under attack. Few states would be hurt more than ours. 11 million Texans below the age of 65 have at least one pre-existing condition. That's half of us. https://t.co/7qThoBLs0t

Text: The number of Texans finally receiving care thanks to this provision includes more than 780,000 people in Harris, 455,000 people in Dallas, 386,000 people in Parker & Tarrant, and 321,000 people in Bexar. Big reason why we've seen our uninsured rate drop since the ACA was passed.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let's immediately reunite separated families. But let's also refuse to be a nation that indefinitely locks away these families in cages for doing what any of us would do for our own children. For seeking refuge in a country comprised of immigrants & asylum seekers the world over.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We marched, called, stood up and spoke out because we believed America to be a place that doesn't take kids from their moms and dads. But we also believe America to be a place that doesn't indefinitely detain families & children in camps. If we don't continue to act, it will be.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Looking at this executive order, how does it reunite kids with their parents?
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The United States of America separated more than 2,000 children from their parents. This country can and must reunite those families. https://t.co/B4pd0EOX41
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: There are currently private prisons and private immigrant detention centers that have established massive political action committees (PACs). We should end all three.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Instead of indefinitely keeping families in cages and camps, the family case management program offered a different, more humane path: requiring asylum seekers to check in for their appointments. 99% of participants successfully attended their court appearances and ICE check-ins.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The family case management program only cost $36 a day per family compared to $319 per person indefinitely kept in detention.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: While 99% of participants attended their ICE check-ins and appointments, a full 100% attended their court hearings. That's according to DHS' Office of Inspector General.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: /54 NEAR EL PASO: U.S. Reps. @BetoORourke & @JoaquinCastrotx arrived in Tornillo, Texas, today to tour temporary detention facilities housing immigrant minors separated from their parents.  (📸: @SalgadoPhoto_) https://t.co/cgG94LqzS6
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I was able to visit the children being held in Tornillo. While I am grateful to those who are caring for these kids, the bottom line is that taking kids from their parents and failing to reunite them afterwards is cruel and inhumane. Now we need to make sure it’s un-American.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I met children who had been in detention for over 3 months; kids whose parents had already been deported back to Guatemala; kids who had no idea when or if they’d see their parents again.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I met officials from HHS & contractor who built Tornillo tent city (BCFS) for these kids. They agreed that this crisis was imposed by the Trump administration - that the tent camps at Tornillo would never have been built had Trump not taken kids from their parents at the border.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: What HHS/ORR could not tell me is why they share info about the sponsors (family in the U.S.) for these kids with ICE — the agency tasked with deporting undocumented migrants. Before a kid is placed they get immigration status on everyone in the sponsor’s household.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I met 7 girls who had just arrived at Tornillo this morning. They’ve been in detention for weeks at other locations. Made the journey on their own, hoping to join family here in the U.S.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: HHS unable to answer: if total number of families apprehended is down over last year; if total number of unaccompanied kids is up only 4%, then why are we keeping kids longer? Avg stay in detention for kids has gone from 34 days to 56 days. Many kids staying longer than that.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
This agreement bw ICE and HHS “represents a dramatic change from past practice—replacing the best interests of children with the operational expediency of immigration enforcement.”

https://t.co/uyYcUoZoYe

Text: Justice Kennedy's retirement opens up a lifetime appointment to the Supreme Court. Any nomination to that seat must live up to the words written above the steps of the highest court in the land, "equal justice under law."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: This means defending and expanding civil rights, voting rights, and workers' rights. It means protecting a woman's right to choose. And upholding protections for those with pre-existing conditions who can finally see a doctor and get the care they need.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It means a new justice who will safeguard the rights of the LGBTQ community. Finally get big money out of politics. End gerrymandering. And ensure every single person coming before that highest court is treated with respect and dignity.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In the last week alone, the Supreme Court has issued close rulings on the president's Muslim ban, on workers’ rights, on voting rights, on gerrymandering, and on a woman’s right to choose. The stakes for this nomination couldn't be higher. We have to get this right.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Thank you @BetoORourke for meeting with our families and getting to know our kids. More than that, thank you for fighting to #ProtectOurCare. https://t.co/sxF4WvmUdl

Text:
100 years ago, Hortense Sparks Ward became the first woman to register to vote in Harris County. Back then, TX was a leader in expanding the vote. Today, we're a non-voting state by design. We must end gerrymandering and return our Democracy to the people.
https://t.co/5ZWtMa7W8U
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Chris Crowley lives in Jubilee Park. Works at a Home Depot Distribution Center in SW Dallas. Doesn't have a car, so he commutes 6 hours a day. 4 buses. 4 trains. Almost 4 miles on foot per day. Doing all he can to make it work, to do the right thing. https://t.co/cWdpBpheQc
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: He starts his shift at 4:30pm. When it ends at 3am, he makes the 3 hour trip back to the house he rents with his parents. Cuts into time with family, time to sleep, to be healthy, to do hobbies, to do the other things he's meant to do.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "It's difficult, but hey, it's life, you know? We either deal with it, or we don't,” Crowley said. “I'm dealing with it the best way I can, and that's to keep going forward and keep staying positive."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We have to match his strength, optimism, determination with a commitment to addressing the persistent inequities in housing, transportation, access to capital & jobs that pay a living wage that are holding too many back. We have to invest in all of our communities, in all people.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: After today, this race to represent Texas in the Senate matters more than ever.

Text: When our nation and our state needs us the most, Texans act. With conviction, with leadership, with a determination to do the most good. Grateful to Mary Lou and the hundreds of East Texans in Longview and beyond who donated supplies. https://t.co/7YiNEHb7mJ

Text: Our country incarcerates a larger proportion of its citizens than any other nation, most of whom are black or brown. African Americans are incarcerated at more than 5 times the rate of whites. https://t.co/iECQmru7n7
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We know that our criminal justice system has created a cycle that puts a disproportionate amount of people of color in jail. African Americans and whites use drugs at similar rates, but the imprisonment rate of African Americans for drug charges is almost 6 times that of whites.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We must urgently address imbalances in our criminal justice system. Start by ending mandatory minimums for minor drug offenses, ending the fed. prohibition on marijuana, ending cash bail, stopping the use of private prisons, and providing an environment that welcomes re-entry.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The Civil Rights Act was signed into law 54 years ago. It was the people -- marching, sitting at lunch counters, being sprayed with fire hoses, bitten by dogs, shedding the blood -- who applied the pressure that formed the political will to force this onto the president's desk.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Signing the legislation, President Johnson said, "This Civil Rights Act is a challenge to all of us to go to work in our communities and our States, in our homes and in our hearts, to eliminate the last vestiges of injustice in our beloved country."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The law was intended, "to enforce the constitutional right to vote, to confer jurisdiction upon the district courts of the US to provide injunctive relief against discrimination in public accommodations, to authorize the AG to institute suits to protect constitutional rights"
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "in public facilities and public education, to extend the Commission on Civil Rights, to prevent discrimination in federally assisted programs, to establish a Commission on Equal Employment Opportunity"
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "All persons shall be entitled to the full and equal enjoyment of the goods, services, facilities and privileges, advantages, and accommodations of any place of public accommodation, without discrimination or segregation on the ground of race, color, religion or national origin."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "The Commission shall investigate allegations in writing under oath or affirmation that certain citizens of the United States are being deprived of their right to vote and have that vote counted by reason of their color, race, religion, or national origin"
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "Desegregation means the assignment of students to public schools and within such schools without regard to their race, color, religion, or national origin"
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: "It shall be an unlawful employment practice for an employer to fail or refuse to hire or to discharge any individual, or otherwise to discriminate against any individual...because of such individual's race, color, religion, sex, or national origin"
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: But 54 years later, we know the Civil Rights Act is not yet fully realized. We know that disparities remain in access to the ballot, access to high-quality public education, access to higher education, access to capital and high-wage jobs, access to equality in our communities.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The march continues at a time when our state implements laws that knowingly make it more difficult for African-American and Latino voters to cast their ballots. When gerrymandering intentionally draws people out of their democracy based on their race and ethnicity.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The march continues at a time when a child’s ZIP code still determines their academic future. When we have a school-to-prison pipeline that leaves black students nearly 4X as likely to be suspended. A graduation rate that finds white students far more likely to receive a diploma.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The march continues at a time when disparities remain in homeownership, employment, and access to capital. When white families have 10 times more wealth than black families. When the unemployment rate is 2X higher for blacks than whites in Texas.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We must meet these challenges with urgency, strength, and determination. We must not become complacent. As President Johnson said on this date in 1964, "My fellow citizens, we have come now to a time of testing. We must not fail."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: On this day 53 years ago, LBJ signed the Voting Rights Act into law. It happened because people were willing to march, to protest, to be arrested, to put their lives on the line crossing the Edmund Pettus Bridge, to apply the pressure that formed the will to get it to his desk.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The work is far from over when we still have racial gerrymandering, people being purged from the rolls, voter ID laws that are designed to make it more difficult for black voters to cast their ballots. When we have parts of the Voting Rights Act being invalidated piece by piece.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Or when we have a nominee for a lifetime appointment on the Supreme Court who has weakened voting rights. We must use today's anniversary as a reminder of what John Lewis said while marching in Selma, "We’re not going back. We’re going to move forward."
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Grateful to everyone who has donated so far — and to all of those on the ground here in El Paso who are helping with temporary shelter, food & other help for these families. I will share volunteer opportunities in El Paso for those in the area as soon as they are shared with me.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I have also spoken with ICE, CBP, El Paso Office of Emergency Mgmt and incoming Congresswoman @vgescobar to see how we can better coordinate releases. My thanks to all those who are working on this.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: @KayZed14 Churches in El Paso have opened their doors and they are providing some of shelter space.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: If you're in the El Paso area, could use your help dropping off fresh fruit -- especially apples, oranges, tangerines, and bananas. They can be brought to the donation site at 1003 E San Antonio Ave.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: While there isn't a need for donations of used clothing at this moment, Annunciation House is looking for NEW socks, underwear, and bras. Sizes small and medium for men, women, and children. They can be brought to the donation site (from 8am-8pm) at 1003 E San Antonio Ave.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Another way to help in El Paso: Organize a group that's willing to get to work preparing and bringing meals to various sites. Could be your school, church, neighborhood group. If you can make meals to feed groups of 50-100 refugees, please email refugees@annunciationhouse.org
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: You can also volunteer directly through Annunciation House. They're looking for people who are willing to drive refugees to the bus station and airport. To get started, email refugees@annunciationhouse.org and a volunteer lead will get back to you.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We’ve conflated the war on terror, the war on drugs, with immigration. This has led to mass deportations & militarization at a time of record safety on the U.S. border. False fear is cynically stoked to harm those who pose no threat to this country. https://t.co/pyzVtfja6R
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: “With the passage of the Patriot act in late 2001, the number of deportations increased again and reached nearly 400,000 in 2009. None of the terrorist attacks involved Mexicans, and none of the terrorists entered through Mexico...all came to the united States on legal visas.”
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: “Yet, Mexicans nonetheless bore the brunt of the deportation campaign launched in the name of the war on terrorism, comprising 72 percent of those removed in 2009.”
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: And, by the way, none of this stuff has worked. As the border became more militarized, and deadlier, immigrants stopped returning to their home countries. In effect, this policy actually increased the number of undocumented immigrants in the U.S.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
Not only that, but walls and militarization of the border have resulted in the deaths of thousands of migrants, including children. We are pushing desperate families to cross in ever more hostile terrain. We are ensuring greater suffering and death.
https://t.co/8v5NKNzQ8H
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: This cynical rhetoric of war, of invasions, of fear — totally disconnected from the truth — has led us to treat our fellow humans in the most inhumane way. And it hasn’t made us safer. We thought we could sacrifice some of our humanity for security, we risk losing both.

Text: “El Paso to me represents America at its very best,” @BetoORourke says as he kicks off his 2020 campaign in Texas https://t.co/aYIcGo5zvO https://t.co/gROqHKEaNh
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It is here, from my hometown of El Paso, that I officially launch this campaign to serve you as the next President of the United States of America.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: This is a campaign for America. For everyone in America. No one written off, no one taken for granted.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Like so many of you, Amy and I have decided that at this moment of truth we must give it our all. This moment is our test - the generations that follow ours, the people of the future, are counting on us - and we cannot be found wanting.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The challenges before us are the biggest of our lifetimes. Millions without healthcare; an economy that works too well for too few and not at all for too many; & the opportunity to avert the worst consequences of climate change fading in the face of our inaction. We must overcome
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: For too long in this country, the powerful have maintained their privilege at the expense of the powerless. They have employed fear and division — based on differences in race or ethnicity, geography and faith — to keep us apart, and angry and afraid of one another.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Unrestrained, money and influence have warped this country’s priorities and its very democracy. It has corrupted our democracy. It has invited cynicism, distrust and disengagement from Americans who see a government in thrall to those who can pay for access and outcomes.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: A vigorous democracy - both economic and political - is the only check on the inertia of power, on the corruption and capture of our institutions, and the only means to elevate the voices and lives of our fellow Americans.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The differences between us — where we live, who we love, to whom we pray, how long our families have been in this country, the color of our skin, the party to which we belong — those differences cannot be allowed to define us or divide us now. Let us be Americans first.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: These challenges and the threats to our democracy cannot be met by half measures or with only half the country. It’s gonna take all we’ve got and it’s gonna take all of us.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: If we believe in universal, guaranteed, high quality healthcare - because we see the consequences to our fellow Americans who go without - then let us come together around a solution.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Universal healthcare means everyone gets primary healthcare, mental healthcare — and universal care also means that every woman makes her own decisions about her own body.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: This means every one of us is able to afford our prescriptions, see a doctor, take our children to a therapist. No one priced out. No one denied care. No one left behind. Universal, guaranteed, high quality health care must be achieved as quickly and as surely as possible.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: If we believe in an economy that works for all, then let us invest in a world class Pre-k through 12 public education system and ensure that we are paying our educators a living wage so that they don’t have to work a second or third job.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s graduate young women and men from high school who are career ready as well as college ready, able to pursue debt-free higher education or a job that provides purpose and a real paycheck. We can do this.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s not diminish the power of unions in this country. Let's strengthen unions in this country and ensure a path to apprenticeships and careers. Guarantee that one job is enough by paying every working American a true living wage.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s support rural America by listening to and partnering with rural communities on infrastructure, schools, hospitals, & broadband. Let’s make sure farmers can make a profit while they grow the food & fiber that feeds and clothes not just this country, but so much of the world.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s ensure everyone can succeed regardless of their family dynamics, their gender, their sexual orientation or their race. Paid family leave. Equal pay for women. No discrimination in the workplace, and access to capital for communities that have been shut out for generations.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: If we believe in real justice reform in the face of the largest prison population on the face of the planet — one disproportionately comprised of people of color — let us not just end the prohibition of marijuana but expunge the record of those arrested solely for possession.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s end cash bail, private prisons, and the war on drugs. Let's confront the true legacy of slavery, of segregation, suppression, of how people have been criminalized & kept down based on their race and ethnicity. Only that truth will allow us to begin to repair the damage done
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: If we believe that this country’s success is premised on the fact that immigrants and asylum seekers from the world over have found a home here, then let us forever free Dreamers from any fear of deportation by making them U.S. citizens.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s bring millions more of our fellow Americans out of the shadows and on to a path to contribute even more to our country’s success.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s not only honor our asylum laws and never again take another child from another parent at their most desperate and vulnerable moment, but guarantee that all separated families are reunited.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s ensure our security not through walls and militarization, but by investing in our ports of entry where the vast majority of everything and everyone that ever comes into this country first enters.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: And if we’re serious about security, let this country of immigrants - republicans, independents and democrats  - rewrite our immigration laws in our own image, from our own experiences, and in the best traditions of this great country.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let us not only ensure that we meet every single part of our obligation to our veterans but that we also make sure that before we enter yet another war that we have exhausted every single peaceful alternative.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: And if the wars we are already in don't have a definition of victory or strategy to win them and bring these service members back home to their families and their communities, we must put an end to them.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let us organize this country around a historic effort to free this economy from a dependence on greenhouse gas emissions, invest in the technologies and jobs in renewable energy that will speed this transition, and reassert our international leadership before it is too late.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We have an opportunity now to meet an existential threat to this planet by ensuring that public health policy, economic policy, and the engine of a far more conscientious capitalism is put to work in service of our ability to meet this challenge of climate change.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: And when we talk about combatting climate change, it is important that this work ensures that every American benefits, including those poor and minority communities that have so often borne the brunt of climate change.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: This country can and must once again take its place as the indispensable leading nation, doing what no other country can, for ourselves and for the world.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: But if we want to do any of this — let us agree that our success as a country is based on the success of this democracy, the greatest mechanism devised to bring forth the power of people.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: So every citizen must be able to cast their vote, have their voice heard. We must sign into law a new voting rights act, we must forever banish big money from our politics, end gerrymandering, and enact same day voter registration in every part of the country.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let us also acknowledge that any hope of full political democracy must be premised on an unwavering pursuit of economic democracy. Every child must see a future for themselves in this country.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The unprecedented concentration of wealth, power and privilege in the United States must be broken apart. Opportunity must be fully shared with all. We must all have the opportunity to succeed. Together. As one country.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Si queremos enfrentar los retos de cuidado de salud por todos; de la reforma migratoria; del cambio climático —necesitamos una democracia en que cada persona puede votar y ofrecer su voz.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Pero también necesitamos una economía donde todos pueden participar, y tener un prospecto de éxito independiente de su genero, de su raza, de los cuantas generaciones su familia tiene a dentro o aparte de los estados unidos.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: El exito de este pais depende en el exito de cada persona en este pais.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let us be clear: we will not be defined by our fears or the smallness of our differences; we will instead be known by our ambitions, our aspirations and the resolve, the creativity, the service and sacrifice by which we will have achieved them.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Our ability to campaign this way as a campaign run for & by people - no PACs, no corporations - people from every state & territory — can bring us together not just in defeating Trump, but in ensuring that we have the full power of people to accomplish this country’s priorities.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I am honored to run to serve you as President of the United States; and I am grateful to each one of you who will join this campaign and commit yourself in service to this great country of ours.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Together, as one country united, we can fulfill the promise of America, to ourselves, to each other, and to every generation that succeeds us.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
I published a @BrennanCenter essay this morning that not only confronts a justice system that is patently unjust -- continuing the legacy of slavery and suppression to criminalize people of color -- but also outlines urgent steps to reform it. Take a look:
https://t.co/2U4xHOuIQg
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It's shameful that our country has the world’s largest prison population. One comprised disproportionately of people of color; built on prosecuting some communities for nonviolent drug offenses & not others, even as people of all races use illegal drugs at roughly the same rate.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It's a prison population perpetuated by a school-to-prison pipeline that starts as early as kindergarten, where a black child is 5x as likely to be suspended or expelled as a white child. Many have joined Michelle Alexander in calling this the New Jim Crow, and for good reason.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: If we are to end mass incarceration, we must confront the fact that every arm of the system is shaped by this legacy — from the over-policing of black and brown neighborhoods, to a process marked by unequal resources, to prisons that set people up for failure rather than reentry.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
Across the country, students, activists, and advocates are laying bare this history and leading the way forward. Because of their efforts and the civil rights heroes before them, I believe we have the opportunity to rebuild our justice system.

This is how I propose we do it:
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: First, we end a failed war on drugs that has long been a war on people, waged on some more than others. We must end the federal prohibition on marijuana and expunge the records of those who were locked away for possessing it.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Second, we stop using mandatory minimums for nonviolent drug offenses — a practice that costs us dearly in both a loss of human potential and a prison budget that has nearly doubled in the past two decades. We must begin treating addiction like the public health concern it is.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Third, we eliminate private, for-profit prisons. No place in our society for a multibillion-dollar industry that profits off human suffering. We will not continue to outsource imprisonment to corporations that have a perverse profit incentive to put more people behind bars.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Fourth, we finally disrupt the cycles of poverty that trap people in a criminal justice system where they do not belong. On any given day, nearly half a million people are in jail — many for misdemeanors — because they cannot afford to post bail.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Let’s end the use of cash bail once and for all and provide states grants to replace these systems. I also support decriminalizing truancy in a flawed system that disproportionately targets black and brown students.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Fifth, we ensure that all people are given an equal opportunity to have their rights respected by our legal system. This means reopening the federal Office of Access to Justice, launched to provide greater resources for indigent litigants in civil, criminal, and tribal courts.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It also means taking on prosecutorial and police misconduct with a fully-staffed Department of Justice that can conduct investigations, provide de-escalation trainings across police agencies, and institute community-based review boards to ensure accountability and transparency.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Finally, we provide meaningful reentry reforms to help reduce recidivism. That starts by banning the box on job applications, returning drivers licenses, allowing access to loans that can unlock skills trainings, and ensuring their constitutional right to vote is protected.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Ultimately, this is about ensuring that every single one of us — regardless of race, ethnicity, or class — can live to our full potential with equal rights and equal dignity. We will build a future that is more just, more fair, and more prosperous for every single person.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Our country has the world’s largest prison population. It is comprised disproportionately of people of color, built by targeting and prosecuting some communities for nonviolent drug offenses and not others. We need real, lasting, meaningful justice reform. The time to act is now. https://t.co/oyPNarjTSC
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Repeal the Hyde Amendment. https://t.co/2IOS3LQJNB
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
“Health care is fundamental to anything else that we want to be able to do."

At our #WorkersForum, @BetoORourke made a compelling case for why America needs universal health care: https://t.co/bqDfPCHU3S

Text: Our thanks to the advocates, activists, and LGBTQ champions across the country who lead the way each day, kept the march for justice going year after year, and ultimately passed the Equality Act in the House today. Together, we will secure full civil rights for LGBTQ Americans.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Brown v. Board was decided 65 years ago but our fight for equality is not over. The work to ensure we have equity and full opportunity in our classrooms, our schools, and our education system must continue. https://t.co/3Bcf2lr7kH
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The work continues when we see an unconscionable achievement gap in our classrooms that is already in full force on the very first day of kindergarten -- where black children are already 10 months behind in math and 12 months behind in reading compared to their white classmates.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The work continues when in that same kindergarten classroom, children of color are five times more likely to be disciplined, suspended, or expelled as a white child -- impacting their opportunity and potential. A school to prison pipeline in full effect at five years old.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The work continues when we see shameful race-based disparities in HS graduation rates, in who can access higher education or skills training, and in who earns a degree. Happening as we fail to invest equitable resources in education and fail to make higher education affordable.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: But I am committed to meeting this challenge with everything we've got. It starts by increasing public school funding for low-income and underserved communities, guaranteeing the equitable distribution of resources, and ensuring teachers reflect the diversity of this country.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: It continues by finally achieving universal pre-k for every three and four-year-old, securing affordable childcare, signing into law paid family leave, and ensuring our country's minimum wage is a living wage so no parent has to work a second or third job to make ends meet.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We will also decriminalize truancy. States like Texas have taken the first step by repealing laws that prosecute children for truancy, but the fines their parents face still loom large in a system that disproportionately targets black and brown students. I will take this on.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: And as president, I will only nominate judges who respect, affirm, and defend Brown v. Board. Andrew Oldham doesn't get nominated. Neither does Wendy Vitter. If you don't believe in civil rights, in equity, in opportunity, you don't belong in a position of public trust.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
As President, here are some immediate steps I will take:

First, I will ensure lawful and humane conditions at our immigration facilities. That means access to medical treatment, mental health care, social workers, and translators. These deaths are preventable.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Second, I will issue an executive order to require detention only for those with criminal backgrounds representing a danger to our communities. We know that these asylum seekers and refugees are harmless kids and families who don’t need to be locked away.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Third, Johana was held at a private ICE facility where the incentive is profit and not security or the well-being of our fellow human beings. I will eliminate all funding for private, for-profit prison operators.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Fourth, I will ensure transparency and accountability in law enforcement, including ICE and CBP. I will create an independent Border Oversight Commission and mandate a uniform process for tracking and preventing deaths at the border.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
Finally, I will establish a first-of-its-kind community-based visa category so communities can welcome LGBTQ refugees through community sponsorship of visas. 

You can find more details and see additional steps here: https://t.co/mrhW5XKacY
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
To ensure this country can live up to its full potential, we must confront the fact that we have an economy that works too well for too few and not at all for too many. At the #BlackPresidentialForum, I announced a plan that does just that. 

Read it here:
https://t.co/cKrpKN3JeI
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Our country has a wealth gap where the median white household is worth 10x that of the median black household. It's unjust, unacceptable & holding every single one of our communities back from reaching its full potential. Small businesses are no exception. #BlackPresidentialForum
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Minority and women owned businesses have been the fastest growing businesses across the country for the past decade. These entrepreneurs helped pull our economy out of the Great Recession. They are staples of our communities, country, and economy. #BlackPresidentialForum
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: But these same entrepreneurs are locked out of the exact resources and capital they need to start their businesses, grow them, and create more jobs. My new plan will unlock half a trillion dollars in opportunity for women and minority owned businesses. #BlackPresidentialForum
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: The plan will spur the development of 200,000 new women and minority owned small businesses by the end of my second term. #BlackPresidentialForum
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: We will root out racism and discrimination in the small business lending market so every business owner, no matter where they live or their background, can get that first loan to start their business or that capital investment to hire additional employees. #BlackPresidentialForum
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: I will triple the federal government’s investment in the Minority Business Development Agency to ensure more entrepreneurs can access mentorship and resources to navigate the challenges of owning a business. #BlackPresidentialForum
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: Finally, my plan calls for shifting $100 billion in government contracts away from large corporations and to small businesses. Half of that opportunity will go to minority and women owned businesses. #BlackPresidentialForum
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In 1999, I started a small business in El Paso that brought dozens of high-wage, high-skilled jobs to the border community. It helps me understand the day-to-day challenges small business owners face -- and those challenges are only amplified for women and communities of color.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text: In Congress, I voted for legislation to ensure minority & women owned businesses had a seat at the table in the government when it came to cracking down on discrimination and to make it easier for small business owners & entrepreneurs to access capital and navigate the tax code.
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
I'm committed to continuing this work and to leveraging the full force of the federal government to expand access to capital and root out institutional racism, sexism, and bias in the small business lending market. 

Read the full plan here:
https://t.co/cKrpKMM7Q8
Name: Beto O'Rourke

Text:
